on":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads named from the definite singular of <i>stig</i>, Old Norse <i>stígr</i> ‘path’, ‘trail’, frequently denoting a position high on a hillside."],"variants":[{"name":"Stien","meanings":["Norwegian: variant of   Stigen  .","German and Flemish: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Augustin</i>, Dutch <i>Augustijn</i> (see   Austin  )."]}]},{"name":"Hvide","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Claus, Eberhard, Hans, Juergen, Markus, Wolfgang.","German and Jewish: variant of   Heid  .","Dutch: rare variant of <b>Van der Heide</b> (see   Vanderheide  ) and, in North America, (also) a shortened form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Heidi","meanings":["(2007: 269; 2010: NA)","German: variant (and also an Americanized form, to retain the second syllable) of   Heide  ."]},{"name":"Heider","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Otto, Fritz, Gunter, Johann, Konrad, Kurt, Matthias, Willibald.","German and Swiss German: topographic name for a heath dweller, a variant of   Heide   + the <i>-er</i> suffix denoting an inhabitant; or a habitational name for someone from any of various places called Heide or Heidau (named with the same term); the placename is common in Silesia, Saxony, and Bohemia."]},{"name":"Heid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Eckhart, Gerd, Gotthilf, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Kurt, Manfred, Ralf, Uli.","German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name from Middle High German <i>heide</i>, German <i>Heide</i> ‘heath, moor, open, uncultivated land’. Compare   Heath  .","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Haido</i>, a short form of any of various compound names beginning with <i>haid</i> ‘heath’ (i.e. wasteland, often with heather)."]},{"name":"Heyde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Achim, Dietrich, Helmut, Volker.","German: topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, unprotected, open country, a variant of   Heide  ."]},{"name":"Hiday","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Heide  ."]}]},{"name":"Juris","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Juris Stigsen Hvide was born in Denmark as the son of Stig Tokesen Galen and Ukendt. He had at least 11 sons and 5 daughters with Margaretha Vognsdatter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1223–1280":"1223–1280","1223–Male":"1223–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1227–Female":"1227–Surnud","1227–Male":"1227–Surnud","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","1230–1264":"1230–1264","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","12